Struggled with the mantra, so much in my life feels beyond my control and honing in on anything I had a 'choice' about felt like a non-starter. It feels like I'm fighting, constantly, on so many fronts. And then it clicked: I choose my battles. From today I'm going to really focus in on choosing which battles are worth it, and crucially choosing not to fight them all. At least... not all at once.

This practice was special for another reason - it's the first time in several years of doing yoga that I've left my hair down, trusting that I'd be able to find what feels good in my own way (I am super sensitive about my hair catching on my clothes, brushing the floor, or sticking to my skin and getting in my face/eyes/nose/mouth). It felt so freeing, I just had to share <3

‚úîÔ∏è Namaste from a rainy California this weekend! I feel like everything gets crazier in the rain, like the drivers, the people, my low grade anxiety (lol) but overall it's chill. Today, I chose to embrace my imperfections. One of the things I've been working on is being more present as a friend. I find that it's a lot easier (but not helpful at all) when listening to friends, or anyone and overshadow their feelings; saying things "oh yeah, that happened to me to!" Or maybe even make them inadvertently feel worse about something they feel is a weakness. One of my friends in particular is person who get often used by people because of her kindness and inability to say no when someone needs help. Which is actually an amazing trait: to be unconditionally helpful. But it definitely sucks to hear how this makes her feel, and I get so caught up witj "oh yeah, you can't be doing that, you gotta be strong because that's not okay" or something along those lines. But then I remember that I'm doing that thing; where I'm taking someone else's moment and making that about me. 

As a parallel metaphor, I guess it's like what inattentive parents do when kids try to tell them about their day and then they get lectured instead of being heard...until eventually the kids don't tell them anything anymore. And those kids grow up to be me, to be us and crave that connection to be heard because the isolation is so deep into the subconscious.

With my friend, I made them a promise that I will do my best to accept that I tend to project and make it about me, and that unless I can help them bake those cakes for the party she wasn't invited to, I'm not going to aggravate it by dumping how I feel about all this into the vent sessions. And I think I picked this up from yoga practice and you, because I've been able to improve my life the most by focusing inward and being allowed to feel whatever I feel instead of being told how to feel.   Thank you friend üôèüíúüåû
